cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=80k6gzYtLn_8_018HJQA6A&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfxQQdBjuJOxN3hkQddzz1kOPYu_sO0m3133pEyAbbVqtQ&amp;oe=69CA1FB6" alt="Slide 3 fra @philosophybreak" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t39.30808-6/653704044_1321505060032402_5647781561733537863_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=104&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzg1NjM3NTI3MTE1MTY4NzIzMg%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjEwODB4MTM1MC5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=HNu4RHPi-EIQ7kNvwFOEY2v&amp;_nc_oc=AdoIime_2j4SxQyfDFmncpMvOD6gFGZxfsPyoi89YKd565lijoyYgwGmA8snPmkiFc8&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;se=7&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=80k6gzYtLn_8_018HJQA6A&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfxS0qQ8GKeA1XzmsXfzTz6uAXllkfQGwFjJOXsdUJhVyw&amp;oe=69CA2A0E" alt="Slide 4 fra @philosophybreak" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /></p><p><strong>🖼️ Slideshow (5 medier)</strong></p><p><strong>@philosophybreak</strong></p><p>Plath’s evocation, taken from her haunting 1963 novel The Bell Jar, might bring to mind the warnings behind Kierkegaard’s “dizziness of freedom”, and Sartre’s comment that “Man is condemned to be free. Condemned, because he did not create himself; because, once hurled into the world, he is responsible for everything he does.” To see how Kierkegaard and Sartre think we can reconcile ourselves to existential freedom, you might like my Existence Precedes Essence on Philosophy Break.<br/>
